names:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Richard de Henhull was born about 1288, in Henhull, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Mrs Richard de Henhull about 1312, in Henhull, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1334."},"et":{"Abt 1288–AFT 1334":"umbes 1288–pärast 1334","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1313–1338":"1313–1338","1288–1334":"1288–1334","1338":"1338","1313":"1313","1334":"1334","Abt 1288":"umbes 1288","AFT 1334":"pärast 1334","1288":"1288","ABT 1312":"umbes 1312","Abt 1313":"umbes 1313","1290":"1290","Henhull, Cheshire, England":"Henhull, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Henhull, Cheshire, England":"Henhull, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1288–AFT 1334":"noin 1288–1334 jälkeen","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1313–1338":"1313–1338","1288–1334":"1288–1334","1338":"1338","1313":"1313","1334":"1334","Abt 1288":"noin 1288","AFT 1334":"1334 jälkeen","1288":"1288","ABT 1312":"noin 1312","Abt 1313":"noin 1313","1290":"1290","Henhull, Cheshire, England":"Henhull, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Henhull, Cheshire, England":"Henhull, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1288–AFT 1334":"environ 1288–après 1334","1290–Female":"1290–Décédée","1313–1338":"1313–1338","1288–1334":"1288–1334","1338":"1338","1313":"1313","1334":"1334","Abt 1288":"environ 1288","AFT 1334":"après 1334","1288":"1288","ABT 1312":"environ 1312","Abt 1313":"environ 1313","1290":"1290","Henhull, Cheshire, England":"Henhull, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","of Henhull, Cheshire, England":"Henhull, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lord Richard de Henhull est né environ 1288, à Henhull, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Mrs Richard de Henhull environ 1312, à Henhull, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé après 1334."},"de":{"Abt 1288–AFT 